metadata.title: Piper J-3 Cub
aws::graph::propositions: Korean War Service of Piper J-3 Cub
The Korean War broke out on 25 June 1950.
The Republic of Korea Air Force flew L-4s to Dongducheon on 26 June 1950.
The L-4 is a military version of the Piper J-3 Cub.
The Republic of Korea Air Force used L-4s to support the ROK 7th Infantry Division.
The Republic of Korea Air Force used L-4s against North Korean military.
Observers in the rear seats of L-4s dropped bombs.
A total of 70 bombs were dropped from L-4s over two days.
L-4 aircraft were switched back to reconnaissance mission after bombs were depleted.
South Korea lost 25 L-4s throughout the Korean War.
The United States Army operated small numbers of L-4s during the Korean War.
The United States Army replaced L-4s with L-16s during the Korean War.
The L-4 performed artillery spotting during the Korean War.
The L-4 performed forward air control during the Korean War.
The L-4 performed reconnaissance during the Korean War.
The L-4 performed the same roles during the Korean War as it had during World War II.
Some L-4s were fitted with a high-back canopy.
The high-back canopy allowed L-4s to carry a single stretcher.
L-4s with high-back canopies were used for medical evacuation of wounded soldiers.

text:
### Korean War service
On 26 June 1950, one day after the Korean War broke out, the Republic of Korea Air Force flew L-4s to Dongducheon to support the ROK 7th Infantry Division against North Korean military by dropping two bombs from an observer in the rear seat. A total of 70 bombs were dropped until the following day, then aircraft were switched back to reconnaissance mission as bombs were depleted. South Korea lost 25 L-4s throughout the Korean War.
The United States Army also operated small numbers of L-4s, but were replaced by L-16 during the war. The L-4 was in service in many of the same roles it had performed during World War II, such as artillery spotting, forward air control and reconnaissance. Some L-4s were fitted with a high-back canopy to carry a single stretcher for medical evacuation of wounded soldiers.
